  "datePublished": "2025-12-31",
  "description": "A monoidal category is a category C equipped with a tensor product ⊗: C × C → C, a unit object I, and coherence isomorphisms for associativity ((A ⊗ B) ⊗ C ≅ A ⊗ (B ⊗ C)) and units (I ⊗ A ≅ A ≅ A ⊗ I). These isomorphisms must satisfy the pentagon and triangle coherence conditions, ensuring that all ways of re-associating and inserting units agree.\nA monoidal category is the categorical generalization of a monoid: where a monoid has elements combined by an operation with an identity, a monoidal category has objects combined by a tensor product with a unit object. A monoid in the category of sets is an ordinary monoid; a monoid in a monoidal category is a monoid object — an object M with multiplication M ⊗ M → M and unit I → M satisfying the monoid axioms.\n",
  "name": "Monoidal Category",
